<TEXT>
a team of researchers at the national cancer 
institute has received the final goahead for a largescale study 
of cancer deaths among people living near nuclear facilities 
according to the teams leader 
dr john boice chief of radiation epidemiology at the 
institute said wednesday that the project has now been approved by 
an nci technical evaluation committee 
weve gone through three reviews and have gotten all the 
approvals he said adding that the project so far had 
encountered no major glitches 
the us study was prompted by a british survey completed last 
year which found that children and young adults up to the age of 20 
who lived near any type of nuclear facility had an increased 
incidence of leukemia 
were focusing of course on the childhood leukemias because 
thats the concern that has been raised from the english study 
boice said but were going to be looking at all malignancies 
he said the initial phase of the project began early this year 
and is expected to take 18 months to complete 
cancer mortality data are being collected for all counties 
containing or adjacent to nuclear power plants and other nuclear 
facilities using nci files that date back to 1950 
were moving forward linking the large databases together 
boice said all the materials have been collated the counties 
where all the reactors are have been located control counties 
in large part have been selected were matching counties based on 
mean income percentage urban and rural and so forth 
plans for the study which involves four nci researchers and two 
consultants also call for a final phase in which the institute 
would send teams into neighborhoods to interview people about their 
occupations and other factors which can affect cancer rates 
however boice said this would be undertaken only if in fact 
we found anything of particular interest from the initial 
statistical survey if we find that there are no elevations in 
cancer incidence theres little justification to go in and do 
indepth studies he said 
