<DOCNO> AP880706-0033 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the pentagon says the iranian jetliner shot 
down in the persian gulf was broadcasting identification signals on 
two frequencies one of them reserved exclusively for military 
aircraft 
every commercial and military aircraft operating in the united 
states or overseas is supposed to carry what is known as a 
transponder according to pentagon and civilian authorities 
when a radar beam or other radio signal hits the plane it 
activates the transponder to broadcast an identification code under 
a system known as identify friend or foe designed to prevent 
attacks on friendly or civilian aircraft 
a sixmember investigating team headed by rear adm william m 
fogarty arrived in the persian gulf on tuesday and will review 
tapes aboard the american warship the uss vincennes to shed light 
on the tragedy officials said 
commercial and military aircraft normally broadcast on what the 
pentagon calls mode 3 sending a reading of their altitude and a 
fourdigit identification code that is arbitrarily assigned to them 
by air traffic controllers 
only military aircraft broadcast on modes 1 2 and 4 said lt 
brian cullin a spokesman for the navy 
mode 1 is a twodigit signal which describes the mission and 
country of origin of the aircraft said cullin the message is not 
encrypted or put into code that cannot be read by the enemy and 
does not give the type of aircraft involved he said 
mode 2 is not encrypted either and identifies the type of 
airplane the country of origin and the planes unit cullin said 
daniel howard the pentagon spokesman told reporters that the 
iranian aircraft was broadcasting in two modes 
it was squawking on mode3 he said it was also 
sending signals on a military mode mode2 and the signals that 
the vincennes was receiving from that aircraft were signals 
that we had previously identified or associated with an f14 no 
commercial airliners use mode2 
the mode 2 transponder he said is a special piece of 
equipment which has to be put on the aircraft and it can only be 
set on the ground 
another type of transponder designated mode 4 by the pentagon 
is classified and encrypted said cullin the navy spokesman 
futher details were not available 
all four modes of the iff use a mark12 transponder which 
transmits and receives on the dband frequency range which is 
1000 to 2000 megahertz the reply signals use different 
frequencies and package their information in pulses of differing 
lengths said cullin 
it is impossible for normal civilian aircraft to broadcast the 
information that would be carried by a mode 2 transmission 
according to pentagon and civilian authorities 
the transponder would have to be altered by the addition of 
circuit boards or other equipment in order to transmit in mode 2 
according to navy and civilian experts 
bill reed a spokesman at alliedsignal incs bendix 
communications division in towson md says airliners are normally 
equipped with two transponders one as a backup bendix 
manufactures transponders but it was not known whether it supplied 
the ones used by the iranian a300 airbus 
identifying friend or foe is a challenge its a process of 
elimination if youve eliminated all the other possibilities you 
are left with only one choice i cant verify hes a friend so 
therefore hes an enemy reed said 
another civilian expert said that mode 2 and mode 3 transmitters 
are basically incompatible 
a military one would send out a signal that would be 
incomprehensible to a civilian air traffic controller said the 
civilian expert who spoke on condition of anonymity on your 
typical us airliner you would not find a military transponder 
a spokesman for the airbus manufacturer in france said the 
airliner was delivered to iran air six years ago with two 
transponders aboard that should have responded to identification 
requests from the cruiser 
the airbus spokesman david velupillai did not specify whether 
the transponders were calibrated to broadcast at civilian or 
military frequency 
</TEXT>
