<TEXT>
the national health service britains cherished 
cradletogave health care system has officially hit middle age 
and at 40 years old the 41billionayear giant is showing signs 
of a midlife crisis 
parties and political shouting matches marked the services 
birthday tuesday 
in parliament prime minister margaret thatcher shouting above 
opposition jeers denied she is bent on dismantling the cornerstone 
of the welfare state 
labor lawmakers recalled with pride the day that a socialist 
dream was realized with the establishment of a service designed to 
give free health care to every briton rich or poor 
the national health service is the socialism that people want 
and understand labor party deputy leader roy hattersley told an 
anniversary rally in glasgow scotland 
for their part health authorities threw parties for the 
nations first babies born free on july 5 1948 the day the 
postworld war ii labor party governments system of socialized 
medicine took effect 
from costing about 1 billion in 1949 the national health 
service bill has soared to about 41 billion a year it narrowly 
outstrips defense spending and is the second biggest item of state 
spending behind social security 
with 12 million staff from cleaners to brain surgeons the 
service is also the biggest employer in western europe 
it provides treatment from flu shots to heart transplants for a 
million patients a year only 10 percent of britons choose private 
treatment 
doctors who pioneered the system recalled tuesday how its birth 
ended the fear of being ill and penniless 
i remember the patients i had tried to visit at home who might 
not answer the door because a young doctors visit wasnt worth the 
cost they could ill afford said sir anthony alment who went on 
to become president of the royal college of obstetricians and 
gynecologists 
despite soaring expenditures the waiting list for hospital beds 
is about 700000 there are periodic national furors such as last 
winter when a child died after a long wait for heart surgery at a 
birmingham hospital 
since she came to power in 1979 the health service has been a 
sensitive topic for mrs thatcher 
mrs thatcher regularly reels off statistics showing that health 
spending has risen by nearly onethird since she took office but a 
common perception of cuts by the conservatives remains 
she has ordered a wideranging review of the health service 
which is due to be released this autumn 
the move and ideas being bandied about such as hospital stay 
charges and tax breaks for private health insurance have increased 
suspicions that she is aiming to reduce state health care to a 
secondrate system for the poorest 
britain spends less than most other western democracies on 
health about 6 percent of its gross national product compared 
with 105 percent consumed by the united states mainly private 
system and 92 percent in west germany 
the conservative government argues the figures are a tribute to 
the efficiency of the british system 
the british medical association the doctors main professional 
body disagrees 
there is in our view a major crisis in the health service 
association chairman dr john marks said this week urging the 
government to increase its funding of the service the 
government of course maintains there is no such crisis most of 
us like most of our patients prefer the evidence of our own 
eyes 
