<TEXT>
the massachusetts supreme court has unanimously 
thrown out a probate court judges order that a mentally retarded 
patient at a state school should undergo testing for aids 
the patient identified by the fictitious name anthony had 
not been tested since the judges order was stayed by a state 
appeals court judge pending the high courts decision the order 
also applied to another unidentified male patient who allegedly was 
anthonys sexual partner 
the supreme court said probate judge eliot k cohen exceeded his 
guardianship authority when he ordered the walter e fernald state 
school in worcester county to have the patients tested 
denise mcwilliams who is both anthonys attorney and director 
of the aids law project at the gay and lesbian advocates and 
defenders organization in cambridge said she was pleased with the 
decision but said it was very limited in its terms 
the justices she noted did not consider larger issues 
concerning state legal requirements on written informed consent 
from patients before tests for acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
can be made and their results disseminated 
the justices said they didnt take up those issues because it 
is clear that the probate and family court judge did not have 
authority to assume control of the department and to order the 
department to conduct tests on anthony and another party 
the judge in effect and incorrectly usurped the function of 
the executive branch of the state government according to the 
courts decision 
mary breslauer spokeswoman for the attorney generals office 
which represented the state department that operates the 
institution said it was gratified that the high court agreed 
with our position that the trial judge had overstepped his boundary 
by ordering an aids test 
cohen had ordered anthony and the other patient to be tested for 
aids even though that was not the issue before him 
the state had asked cohen to amend an earlier courtordered 
medical plan for anthony so he could have a venereal wart removed 
by the time cohen heard the case the wart had disappeared and all 
parties concerned from anthonys physician to department 
officials asked that the request be dismissed 
but cohen concluded in his ruling that the wart the 
unrestrictive setting at the mental health facility and anthonys 
alleged homosexual activity were conducive to aids and the 
potential spread thereof 
