<TEXT>
four years after vietnam veterans settled a 
lawsuit against manufacturers of the herbicide agent orange a 
federal judge has set into motion the distribution of 240 million 
to be used for disability payments and other assistance 
us district judge jack b weinstein of brooklyn announced 
plans tuesday for handing out the settlement money which was freed 
after the us supreme court last week removed the last legal 
obstacle in the lengthy agent orange litigation 
cash payments and other benefits could be available early next 
year according to the distribution agreement 
the class action initiated in 1978 was settled in may 1984 
when seven chemical companies that manufactured agent orange agreed 
to pay 180 million the settlement money has grown to 240 million 
through interest during the appeals process 
the distribution plan has two major components a 170 million 
program to provide cash benefits to longterm totally disabled 
veterans and to the families of veterans whose deaths were believed 
to have been linked to agent orange and a 52 million program to 
fund social service projects that benefit veterans and their 
families 
in addition 5 million will be distributed to vietnam veterans 
in australia and new zealand another 13 million will be used to 
pay lawyers fees and costs for administering the distribution plan 
agent orange was used as a defoliant in southeast asia during 
the 1960s by the us military 
the herbicide contains the highly toxic dioxin and veterans 
contend that exposure to it causes cancer and other illnesses 
the chemical companies have said there is no scientific proof 
linking dioxin exposure to human illness and the settlement does 
not include an admission of fault by the manufacturers 
the companies sued were monsanto dow uniroyal hercules th 
agriculture and nutrition diamond shamrock and thompson 
to date about 250000 people have filed preliminary claims for 
compensation weinstein set a jan 1 1989 deadline for 
applications 
of the claims to date only about 40000 to 60000 may be 
eligible for the payments said john gomperts an attorney working 
on the settlement 
gomperts said the first payments could be sent out within six 
months 
projections estimate the disability benefits would average 
5700 to 12800 to be paid over a number of years 
a veteran would have to prove total disability and that he 
or she was exposed to agent orange while in vietnam 
the death payments estimated from 1800 to 3400 would be 
paid to families in a lump sum 
the assistance program will issue grants and distribute money to 
social service projects over a sevento10year period with an 
emphasis on projects to benefit vietnam veterans children with 
birth defects 
ten million dollars from the assistance programs 52 million 
budget would be placed into a special reserve for 25 years to cover 
possible claims in state courts and also to compensate injured 
vietnam veterans exposed to agent orange should future evidence 
indicate a legally cognizable link between exposure to the 
herbicide and specific ailments 
weinstein also ruled that 2440 veterans who opted out of the 
settlement on the advice of their lawyers could be reinstated as 
members of the class and receive benefits from the fund 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
veterans can receive information about the agent orange 
settlement fund by calling a tollfree number in new york state 
the number is 18008321303 outside of new york the number is 
18006451355 
</TEXT>
