<TEXT>
nine colleges hope to stem a growing shortage 
of black public school teachers with a 3 million effort to 
convince minorities they have a future in the classroom 
six historically black colleges in five southeastern states will 
work with three traditionally white universities to provide 
enrichment and leadership programs aimed at increasing the supply 
of minority teachers 
there is a decline nationwide of minorities going into 
teaching said billy black president of albany state college 
one of the schools participating in the program the idea is to 
develop programs to reverse that trend 
blacks currently make up an estimated 162 percent of the total 
public school population in the region and 69 percent of the 
teaching force 
in seven years predictions are that minorities will make up 30 
percent of all public school students but only 5 percent of the 
teachers 
of the estimated 15 million new teachers needed by the 
mid1990s at least 500000 should be minorities to serve the needs 
of minority students black said 
historically black albany state is a part of the university 
system of georgia other black schools taking part in the program 
are the tuskegee university in tuskegee ala bethunecookman 
college daytona beach fla xavier university of new orleans 
grambling state university in grambling la and johnson c smith 
university of charlotte nc 
the three traditionally white universities taking part are 
harvard university in cambridge mass vanderbilt university in 
nashville tenn and columbia university in new york city 
the consortium will offer a teacher cadet program designed to 
increase the confidence of black students and boost their academic 
skills summer enrichment programs that promote teaching as a 
career and summer scholars programs that enables black students to 
study at harvard 
also planned are faculty exchange and enrichment programs 
minority leadership centers that offer advanced degrees school 
administrators and research efforts aimed at increasing the supply 
of minority teachers 
the programs are being coordinated by the atlantabased southern 
education foundation the bellsouth foundation of atlanta and the 
pew charitable trusts of philadelphia have provided 175 million 
in funding sef hopes to get an additional 125 million from other 
sources 
katherine kinnick of the southern education foundation said 
there are several possible explanations for the black teacher 
shortage including that other careers offer higher pay and that 
the pool of potential teachers is shrinking because fewer blacks 
are going to college 
