<TEXT>
the government has decided to lower the price it 
will pay farmers for rice this year a government spokesman said 
wednesday 
after a heated debate the governing liberal democratic party 
and the agricultural ministry decided to recommend that farmers be 
paid 128 per 132 pounds 46 percent lower than last years price 
said chief cabinet secretary keizo obuchi 
the price will be proposed to the rice council which advises 
the agriculture minister he said the council will consider the 
proposal and make its recommendation to agriculture minister 
takashi sato for a final decision 
distribution of rice in japan is controlled by the government 
which buys rice from the farmers and releases it to the market as 
needed 
the government also postponed introduction of a new method of 
calculating the producers rice price the agriculture ministry 
says the current method which considers all farmers in calculating 
the price sets too high a figure 
the ministry wants to use only farms of more than 37 acres in 
calculating the price said isoshi kajii an agriculture professor 
at tokyo agriculture and engineering university 
because large farms are more cost efficient the new method 
will enable the government to reduce the rice price further he 
said 
kajii said the government delayed introducing the new measure 
for one year as a political move to tame the anger of farmers 
who opposed japans recent opening of beef and citrus markets to 
the united states 
in fiscal 1986 japanese farmers produced 116 million tons of 
rice while japanese people consumed only 108 million tons 
according to the food agency the agency also said japan stockpiled 
18 millon tons of rice as of october 
