<TEXT>
after a fiveyear decline in whale activity in 
massachusetts bay the leviathans seem to be making a strong return 
from more remote sections off the new england coast 
their migration back has delighted tourists and fascinated 
researchers sharing the waters of the stellwagen bank one of the 
nations top areas for recreational and scientific whale 
observations 
mason weinrich director of the cetacean research unit in 
gloucester saw nearly 50 humpback whales surface in stellwagen 
earlier this week it was more whales than he logged in any of the 
past several years 
theres no question there are more whales out there than in 
recent years said weinrich who has been studying stellwagen 
whales since the late 1970s but were not really sure how 
long the whales will stay around 
marine experts say a plentiful supply of small fish and 
microorganisms have drawn the large number of humpback minke and 
other whales from feedings grounds 50 miles east of nantucket back 
to stellwagen located less than 30 miles offshore from boston 
the tiny sand lance a pencilthin fish preferred by several 
species of whales is being noticed in dense concentrations in the 
stellwagen area say experts in addition the small shrimp and 
plankton that right whales strain through their balene plates are 
abundant this year 
some experts theorize the whales return to stellwagen is linked 
to heavy commercial fishing of mackerel and herring which eat sand 
lances 
all the elements are right at the moment for the whales 
said john nicolas biologist at the national marine fisheries 
service in woods hole 
nicolas estimates there may be as many as 100 humpback whales in 
the stellwagen bank and a smaller number minke finback and sei 
whales for the past several years only a few lone humpbacks 
remained in stellwagen by midsummer 
since the mid1980s most of the whales had followed the sand 
lances to the great south canal off nantucket which is too distant 
and the seas are too rough for tourist whale watch voyages 
the humpback whales seen in stellwagen are part of a larger herd 
that feeds from rhode island to maine other humpback herds are 
located off nova scotia greenland and iceland said weinrich 
its been pretty discouraging the last couple years said 
lisa frohock office manager at gloucester whale watch which 
operates a 100foot vessel so far this year its been great we 
go out and the whales are all around 
al avellar owner of the dolphin whale watch fleet in 
provincetown gives a less scientific explanation to the whales 
return 
its like an oldfashioned summer hot and sunny said 
avellar whose boats are taking up to 1000 people to stellwagen 
each day they went away about three weeks ago but theyre 
back 
