states and many are already under expulsion orders 
ira kurzban attorney for the farmworkers said the ins is 
defying congress wishes by demanding documentary proof of 
employment which farmworkers do not have because many had been in 
the country illegally 
the government has imposed an impossible burden of proof 
said the complaint kurzban said the burden of proof should be on 
the ins to disprove the affidavits 
the ins has also held hearings on the permits without 
translators present kurzban said and is not granting required 
temporary work permits during the appeal process 
ins attorney david bernal said the rigorous proof is necessary 
to support the affidavits because it has been determined there 
was fraud in this area 
bernal told atkins that the burden of providing a translator was 
not the governments responsibility and that most farmworkers 
brought someone with them to the ins hearings in any case 
the ins also argued that the district court had no jurisdiction 
because congress specifically said only federal appeals courts 
could hear challenges to the law but kurzban said the suit is 
challenging only ins procedures not the law itself 
