<TEXT>
the federal deposit insurance corp has struck 
out in its initial effort to sell nearly 1 billion in bad loans 
acquired in the largestever government bank bailout officials 
said wednesday 
steven seelig associate director of the fdics division of 
liquidation said a plan approved by the fdic board in february to 
publicly offer the loans from continental illinois corp in six 
large portfolios failed but he said efforts would begin 
immediately to sell the loans in smaller packages 
in the unprecedented bailout the fdic in 1984 pumped 45 
billion 35 billion of it borrowed from the federal reserve 
system into the chicagobased bank to prevent the failure of what 
was then the nations seventhlargest bank 
as part of the rescue the fdic which insures accounts in 
commercial banks up to 100000 took over many of continental 
illinois problem loans and acquired ownership of the banks stock 
it expects to recoup all but 17 billion of the bailout money by 
selling the loans and the stock 
seelig told the fdic board that the agency staff attempted to 
sell the last of the nonperforming loans originally worth 865 
million for a minimum of 299 million 
despite 274 expressions of interest seelig said the fdic found 
only 17 bidders financially qualified to buy the loans only five 
of those actually submitted bids all of which were too low 
the market for large complex troubled credit is thin and 
requires sophisticated buyers he said 
some of the potential buyers were looking to make a quick profit 
by buying the loans cheap and immediately reselling them rather 
than holding the loans and working on collections seelig said 
however he said the fivemonth effort to market the loans in 
large groups turned up investors who could buy smaller batches at 
the fdics asking price 
fdic chairman l william seidman noting a september 1989 
deadline for repayment of the federal reserves 35 billion loan 
said i hope you can move ahead with all deliberate speed 
