<TEXT>
gov robert casey instructed state officials 
wednesday to seek maximum civil penalties and consider criminal 
charges against ashland oil inc for a jan 2 fuel tank collapse 
that polluted two major rivers in three states 
the governor following the recommendations of a task force 
report that he released at a news conference told the department 
of environmental resources to seek maximum civil damages against 
ashland he declined to say how much the damages might total 
casey also asked the state attorney general to consider criminal 
charges against the company but said he would not recommend filing 
charges against individuals 
in us district court meanwhile ashland promised in a consent 
decree to pay 680000 in federal cleanup expenses and to clean 
contaminated soil and ground water at its floreffe terminal south 
of pittsburgh 
the us environmental protection agency which joined in the 
consent decree reserved the right to sue ashland separately for 
damages an epa spokesman in philadelphia declined to say if the 
agency would sue 
keith welks chief counsel of the state der and head of the 
governors task force said ashland and its subcontractors 
displayed a pervasive pattern of neglect at virtually every 
step in taking down an old steelwalled vessel at its whiskey 
island terminal near cleveland and reconstructing it in floreffe 
among other things welks said the company failed to test the 
toughness of the 40yearold steel used in the tank did not xray 
enough welds on the reconstructed tank or repair defective welds 
found and did not test the reconstructed tank with water first 
a critical dimesized flaw in the steel located near a weld 
probably would have been discovered had ashland acted properly 
welks said 
in general we found that there was a failure of leadership by 
ashland he said employees did not know what each others 
responsibilities were they did not know what their own 
responsibilities were 
ashland officials said the state report largely duplicates its 
own study 
in a statement from its headquarters in ashland ky the 
company expressed disappointment with the governors decision and 
said ashland has paid 85 million so far in company and government 
expenses and in damages to individuals and businesses 
weve been as open as we possibly can be said ashland 
spokesman roger schrum 
casey asked the state legislature for power to regulate 
aboveand belowground fuel tanks 
voluntary industry standards do not adequately protect the 
public he said 
the governor also urged the state senate to remove from pending 
toxic waste cleanup legislation what he called crippling 
antipeople propolluter amendments that would exempt fuel tanks 
from coverage 
the aboveground tank at floreffe burst minutes after the 
company filled it with 39 million gallons of no 2 fuel oil for 
the first time since its reconstruction the report said the state 
accepted previous findings that blamed the collapse on the flaw in 
the metal cold weather and the pressure of the fuel oil 
the collapse spilled an estimated 511000 gallons into the 
monongahela river cutting off water service to 20000 pittsburgh 
residents for a week 
