fighting flared between palestinian 
guerrillas in beiruts bourj elbarajneh refugee camp wednesday 
after the collapse of algeriansponsored negotiations to end the 
nineweekold bloodletting 
police said loyalists of plo chief yasser arafat traded mortar 
and rocket fire with syrianbacked rivals of col saeed mousas 
fatahuprising breakaway faction after three algerian envoys left 
the camp 
two people were killed and 11 were wounded in the exchanges 
police said bringing the overall toll to 160 killed and 629 
wounded since fighting broke out on may 1 for control of bourj 
elbarajneh and the nearby chatilla camp 
chatilla fell to fatahuprising guerrillas june 27 leaving 
bourj elbarajneh as the palestine liberation organizations last 
stronghold in the lebanese capital 
the algerians would not say why the talks failed but a police 
spokesman later explained that the dissidents insisted on 
withdrawal of arafats followers from the shantytown 
the policeman who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
algerians were working on a formula for peaceful coexistence 
between the two sides 
the negotiations had included syrian army officers 
representatives from the two warring factions and other palestinian 
and leftist lebanese groups mohammed taher a member of algerias 
ruling national liberation front led the algerians 
taher told the dissidents before he and his team withdrew that 
algeria will not sponsor the evacuation of palestinians from 
anywhere the police spokesman reported algeria is a leading 
arab supporter of the palestinian cause and the plo 
neutral plo factions also sided with the algerians 
the police spokesman had said earlier that the mediators were 
discussing withdrawal of the remaining 100 guerrillas of arafats 
mainstream fatah faction from bourj elbarajneh to south lebanon 
where the plo has bases 
mousa broke with the plo in 1983 
fatah officials said mousas gunners wrecked 80 percent of bourj 
elbarajneh in the past two months only 3000 of the camps 20000 
residents remain inside 
the loss of chatilla and the weakened defensive position in 
bourj elbarajneh are setbacks for arafat who has been trying to 
rebuild his lebanese power base since he was forced out of beirut 
when israel invaded in 1982 
a fatah official in bourj elbarajneh who also spoke on 
condition of anonymity said the fatah guerrillas have accepted 
the evacuation idea in principle but are demanding guarantees that 
they will not be attacked when they leave the camp 
he said about 150 fatah fighters have left the camp peacefully 
since the latest bout of fighting erupted monday 
a fatahuprising official known as abufadi hammad said arafats 
men would only be allowed to evacuate after they hand over their 
weapons 
the algerians were to guarantee the safe conduct for arafats 
withdrawing fighters fatah also asked that other plo factions not 
involved in the battles escort the guerrillas on the 25mile trip 
south to the lebanese port city of sidon 
mousas forces have prevented libyan mediators who played a 
key role in evacuating arafats men from chatilla after it fell 
from continuing their efforts the fatah official said he said the 
dissidents have banned 26 libyan military observers from entering 
bourj elbarajneh in the past few days 
libya has become one of arafats main allies and its leader 
col moammar gadhafi has been trying to reconcile the plo chief 
with syrian president hafez assad 
assad and arafat met in damascus in april and again in algiers 
in june but they have failed to patch up their bloody fiveyear 
feud over who would control the palestinian guerrilla movement 
the interpalestinian war has capped six years of assaults on 
the camps the israelis devastated the shantytowns during the 1982 
invasion in september 1982 israelibacked christian militiamen 
massacred hundreds of refugees in chatilla and sabra the smallest 
of the three beirut camps 
sabra then was demolished in a crackdown by syrianbacked shiite 
moslems 
thousands more were killed in three years of fighting between 
the guerrillas in the camps and syrianbacked shiite moslem 
militias that ended earlier this year 
