minister noboru takeshita japan will donate 4 million to invite 
us scientists and engineers to the country open research 
laboratories to americans and boost the number of foreign 
researchers invited on scholarships from 28 to 200 
washington long has demanded more funding and a commitment to 
balance the flow of researchers and information getting tough as 
critics especially us industry call for an end to what they say 
has been japans free ride 
the japan center at the university of north carolina estimates 
that 15000 japanese students and researchers enter us 
institutions a year five times the number of americans coming to 
japan 
japan earned 22 billion from foreigners in fiscal 1986 on its 
patent licenses and other technology information while it paid 
24 billion over 80 percent of that to the united states 
hiroshi inose head of the national center for science 
information system discounts tokyos latest moves 
its a big step but its still symbolic said inose 
developer of the governments fifthgeneration computer research 
project and one expert consulted by the government over the 
bilateral science pact 
we should establish a sort of system of substantial scale in 
terms of money or university chairs and positions and let this be 
understood by the americans and the europeans inose said they 
will decide whether they want to come over 
leading japanese scientists many of whom have studied or worked 
in america agree that the time has arrived for japan to repay its 
debt 
my generation has all gone to the united states to study 
japan just preaches about international cooperation but it really 
has to start putting out more funds like the us government 
which has spent so much over the years tokyo university 
professor shoji tanaka one of the worlds leading 
superconductivity researchers said in an interview 
inose who invented the digital telephone switch as a researcher 
at the university of pennsylvania and bell telephone in the late 
1950s agrees 
i have repeatedly told the government that the united states 
has spent a great deal to invite japanese scientists and engineers 
on fulbright scholarships i dont think we ever reciprocated for 
that 
the usjapan agreement on cooperation in science and 
technology was first signed in 1980 to promote basic research in 
nonenergy areas it was renewed five times since 1985 and after 
10 months of negotiations ending in june officials agreed to a new 
pact effective from 1988 to 1993 
the largely symbolic agreement was not controversial until 
tensions mounted over japans trade surplus when fullscale talks 
to renew the pact began last year the united states surprised 
japan by laying down a list of stringent rules to balance bilateral 
cooperation 
in 11thhour talks in june us negotiators won a major 
concession when japan agreed to restrict the publication of joint 
technology with possible military application and to restrict the 
transfer of such information 
technological exports include information and licenses on old 
and new technology such as submarinesilencing equipment toshiba 
machine co sold to the soviet union in violation of a western 
block trade agreement 
no provisions exist under japanese law to prevent the 
dissemination of scientific and technological information developed 
for peaceful purposes but officials say they can adhere to the 
pact because both sides have agreed to distribute the results of 
their joint research as widely as possible 
in tokyo however the feeling pervades that japan is being 
forced to comply with a pact of benefit only to washington to us 
in japan it appears we are under the pressure of the us 
government inose said 
japanese officials point to a number of problems overlooked by 
washington 
nagahide onozawa will oversee 100 of the foreign researchers 
under the jurisdiction of the governmental japan society for the 
promotion of science he says promising american scientists 
eligible for 30 to 40 of the endowments are not the most likely 
candidates to respond to the new program 
apart from the problems of language and style of living many 
researchers at the start or the peak of their careers are not that 
interested in coming to japan theyre afraid of being left 
behind by their colleagues back home 
tanaka head of the governments international superconductivity 
technology center questions the intentions of the us government 
and industry 
tanaka found no takers when he recently visited the united 
states in an attempt to woo american corporate participation in the 
new superconductivity project despite paranoia that japan was 
taking the lead in the field which promises a bounty in terms of 
application patents 
tanaka said nationalism is driving the us government as it 
closes off symposiums on superconductivity to foreign participation 
in a bid to take first place in the field yet superconductivity is 
one area us officials selected for joint research in drawing up 
the new bilateral agreement 
tanaka and other scientists say us industry is not interested 
in joining costly programs like the one he heads 
william norris chairman emeritus of the control data corp 
echoed the opinion of us firms when he told a recent us senate 
space subcommittee that japan should give us firms free 
access in exchange for the technology it has developed from 
american research 
foreign ministry spokesman yoshifumi matsuda said in a briefing 
the americans major interest is in japanese institutions of 
applied science rather than basic science most of the applied 
science institutions here are private and we cannot control the 
private sector 
japans private industry footed 803 percent compared with the 
50 percent us firms put up in america of the 68 billion the 
nation spent on research and development in 1985 
of the research in japanese industrial laboratories almost 94 
percent of the outlays went into experimental development and 
applied research a fact not overlooked by us industry 
japans technological standing inose said is worldclass in 
fields like computer memories and biotechnology the united 
states cannot excel in every area and they have to think about an 
international division of labor 
