<TEXT>
the senate voted wednesday by a vetoproof 
7223 margin to make companies provide workers and local officials 
60 days advance notice of plant closings and large layoffs 
nineteen republicans many of them up for reelection this year 
joined democrats in support of the mandatory notices which 
president reagan cited as his primary reason for vetoing in may a 
massive overhaul of the nations trade laws 
the bill requires any company or plant employing more than 100 
people to give advance written notices to affected workers and 
local officials of any layoff or closing of a facility involving 50 
or more fulltime employees 
exempted from the requirement are layoffs caused by 
unforeseeable circumstances at the time the notices should have 
been provided and businesses that might be hurt by the notices in 
trying to raise capital in order to keep a plant open 
the vote occurred after democrats rejected a lastditch 
amendment by sen dan quayle rind a leader of the opposition to 
the measure to raise the thresholds to half a plants workforce 
and 75 or more workers 
with the higher thresholds quayle said he and other republicans 
would try to persuade reagan not to veto the bill 
weve compromised far enough said sen howard metzenbaum 
dohio this is a matter of simple human decency american 
workers are entitled to 60 days advance notice before losing their 
jobs 
house majority leader thomas foley dwash said the house 
likely will take up the measure early next week 
after delaying the vote for two weeks republicans agreed 
earlier wednesday to end what critics had claimed was a filibuster 
aimed at denying democrats a chance to override reagans expected 
veto before the democratic national convention begins july 18 
only five senate republicans warren rudman and gordon humphrey 
of hew hampshire james mcclure and steve symms of idaho and 
malcolm wallop of wyoming voted to continue the stalling tactics 
i would hope that the president would see there are sufficient 
votes to override a veto and that will mean that he wont veto 
it metzenbaum said 
had the measure been law the past two years more than 800000 
workers who were laid off annually in 1986 and 1987 would have 
received the advance notices he said 
democrats voted unanimously for the measure while picking up the 
support of nine more republicans than they had when they failed to 
override reagans veto of the trade bill last month 
i dont know what the presidents going to do when he gets 
this bill said senate minority leader bob dole of kansas who 
called the vote a big victory for the labor leaders in america 
reagan had indicated he would sign a trade bill that did not 
include the plant closing measure but the aflcio said it would 
withdraw its pivotal support for the trade legislation without 
enactment of a separate plant closing law 
aflcio president lane kirkland called wednesdays vote margin 
overwhelming and said it is a welcome message for american 
workers 
republicans last week succeeded in stalling the vote until after 
the july 4th holiday only five of them voted with democrats to 
break the filibuster then 
im certain that its going to pass and become law sen 
phil gramm rtexas said just before wednesdays vote the 
tragedy is that were doing this all because of politics 
with polls showing that 80 percent of americans favor making 
companies provide their employees advance notice of layoffs the 
issue has given democrats a major opening to attack reagan 
administration economic policies 
democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis has endorsed 
the idea of federally mandated advance notices nationwide even 
though he opposed them on other than a voluntary basis in 
massachusetts as governor he feared that businesses would 
relocate in other states 
republicans stalled action on the bill last week by trying to 
make democrats vote first on the massachusetts voluntary notice law 
that dukakis has touted as an example of his concern for workers 
democrats balked at allowing a vote then on a day that dukakis 
was making a series of courtesy calls in the capitol that would 
have enabled republicans to claim as a rejection of the 
massachusetts governor 
vice president george bush has endorsed voluntary notices the 
same position taken by the reagan administration the last four 
years and conditioning federal contracts and tax incentives to 
pledges by companies to provide advance notices as part of their 
affirmative action plans 
a bureau of labor statistics study in may showed that more than 
400000 workers in just 49 states lost their jobs last year to mass 
layoffs and plant closings 
the bureau concluded in a 1987 study of layoffs in six states 
that 64 percent of the workers affected received no advance notice 
they would lose their jobs and another 16 percent were told less 
than two weeks in advance 
