<TEXT>
when members of president jose sarneys 
entourage carried japanesemade personal computers on a recent trip 
to the united nations journalists wondered whether the brazilian 
officials were flouting their own trade laws 
the incident highlighted a controversial computer industry 
protection law that keeps large chunks of brazils growing computer 
market offlimits to foreignowned multinationals 
on june 8 one day after he addressed the united nations sarney 
was asked at a news conference to comment on the computers his 
answer was a terse all i will say is that now i will take 
another question later an official denial of any wrongdoing was 
issued 
for more than a decade local companies have been protected by 
the socalled market reserve policy that gives them the 
exclusive right to manufacture and sell microcomputers and 
minicomputers in the country 
multinationals such as unisys corp and international business 
machines corp are allowed only to produce and market the more 
powerful mainframe computers 
almost four years ago this practice was formalized with passage 
of brazils controversial informatics law 
it has frustrated computer companies from the united states and 
other countries wanting a greater share of what local press reports 
say is the worlds sixthlargest computer market after the united 
states japan west germany britain and france 
the laws advocates say that without market reserve local firms 
would never survive the competition from multinationals and brazil 
would never achieve technological autonomy 
according to the special secretariat of informatics the 
government agency that sets the rules for the computer industry 
the number of local companies in the sector went from nine to 350 
in little more than 10 years the number of multinationals rose 
from two to just 30 
more than half of brazils 326 billion computer market last 
year was kept offlimits to foreign firms 
marketreserve opponents concede the policy was instrumental in 
developing a thriving domestic computer industry but they say it 
has outlived its usefulness and now prevents brazil from obtaining 
uptodate technology 
market reserve they say is responsible for brazils producing 
more expensive and obsolete clones of foreign computers the policy 
has spawned a growing black market which press reports estimate at 
some 300 million worth of computers and components a year 
geraldo moura press spokesman of the finance ministry said 
there were no official figures on the volume or value of computers 
smuggled into the country but he said computer smuggling was 
widespread and a very easy thing to get away with 
one of the laws major opponents is the united states which 
claims its industry has suffered some 2 billion in lost sales 
because of what it considers an unfair brazilian trade practice 
last year the united states was on the verge of imposing trade 
sanctions against brazil because of what it considered an unfair 
interpretation of the socalled equivalency principle used to 
determine what foreign software programs could enter the country 
under this principle foreign software could be imported as long 
as no locally made equivalent was available 
after lengthy negotiations the sanctions were suspended in june 
1987 when the united states received assurances the software issue 
would receive fairer treatment 
but a few months later the informatics secretariat banned the 
entry of the msdos software program produced by microsoft corp in 
retaliation president reagan announced on nov 13 his intention to 
raise tariffs of brazilian exports to the united states 
brazil soon started backtracking and in january decided to allow 
microsoft to market its msdos 33 the most sophisticated version 
of the operating system software for personal computers 
two months later the informatics secretariat refused to license 
a locally made computer that apple computer inc charged was a copy 
of its macintosh model 
and in may sarney signed a law that makes it easier for 
foreignmade software programs to enter the country and offers 
copyright protection for the authors of software programs 
the informatics secretariat believes it has taken sufficient 
steps to avoid trade retaliation by the united states and does not 
expect sanctions to be imposed said murilo ramos a spokesman 
one western diplomat who requested anonymity agreed saying 
the trade sanctions will probably once again be suspended because 
at least for the moment there is no reason for retaliations 
but while brazil seems to be inching towards a more flexible 
stance on its market reserve policy it has no intention of 
abandoning it at least not in the foreseeable future 
jose ezil veiga da rocha head of the informatics secretariat 
said brazilian companies will continue receiving government 
protection until they can stand on their own two feet and compete 
on the international market he did not want to predict how long 
this would take 
</TEXT>
