<TEXT>
consumer advocate ralph nader asserted 
wednesday that lloyds of london has an unregulated secretive 
role in the us insurance industry and was a major force behind 
the nationwide liability crisis 
he said the giant insurance underwriting exchange looking for 
ways to make up losses sustained during highly publicized internal 
scandals helped spawn higher rates in the united states and 
reduced compensation for victims in liability cases 
nader added his voice to recent charges by a number of states 
that the insurance industry touched off the crisis by conspiring to 
stop providing some kinds of liability coverage 
he released a report titled goliath lloyds of london in the 
united states which charged that lloyds was a driving force 
behind the commercial insurance crisis of the mid1980s 
lloyds wields its influence in the united states primarily as a 
reinsurer providing insurance for us companies in exchange for 
sharing the risk of their own policies as such it dictates to a 
remarkable degree both the rate and policy decisions in the us 
propertycasualty insurance industry nader contended at a news 
conference 
it is a foreign unregulated secretive powerful lever on who 
gets insurance when and at what price in the united states 
whether it is the ability of a day care center a trucking firm a 
school a hospital a mass transit system or a farmer to get 
affordable insurance nader said 
lloyds of london spokesman david larner said we have not 
seen the report and we are not going to comment until we have had a 
chance to study it 
the 300yearold lloyds has in the last decade faced a series 
of insurance scandals and suffered heavy losses insuring ships and 
cargos in the persian gulf 
as a result nader asserted lloyds in the mid1980s saw an 
opportunity in the united states and by generating a fictional 
impression that there is a litigation explosion and a lawsuit 
crisis in the united states worked with us companies for 
legislation reducing victims rights in liability cases and 
restrictions on coverage for various policies 
that resulted in increased rates for what coverage could be had 
and the ensuing crisis he said 
this year 18 states have filed lawsuits accusing 32 insurance 
companies and underwriting agencies of engaging in secret 
agreements to eliminate pollution insurance and general liability 
for damage discovered after expiration of a policy 
the suits also claim that the companies got major reinsurers 
including lloyds to threaten to boycott any us insurance 
company that provided broader coverage 
the report called for greater us regulation of reinsurers and 
alternative reinsurance programs to be set up by federal and state 
governments 
